<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,151,176]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Readily recognized by the following characters: Body rounded or ovoid, tumid, 
<quantity box="[1208,1346,151,176]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.85" metricValueMax="3.5" metricValueMin="2.2" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" unit="mm" value="2.85" valueMax="3.5" valueMin="2.2">2.2–3.5 mm</quantity>
in total length, with densely distributed, lanceolate silvery or silky, scale-like setae which are very easily rubbed off (during collecting and/or mounting); head short and broadened, wider than high in frontal view; dorsal body surface weakly shining, usually with dark, simple setae, in addition to scalelike setae; eye small; antenna generally slender and long; bases of mesepisternum and metapleuron often roundly infuscate; hemelytron strongly declivous at cuneal fracture; left paramere thickened; and endosoma usually elongate, C- or J-shaped, often with median appendages. Detailed diagnoses and taxonomic characters are provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh" box="[989,1140,367,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. (1984) Revision of the Phylinae (Hemiptera, Miridae) of the Indo-Pacific. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 177, 1 - 476." type="journal article" year="1984">
Schuh (
<number box="[1074,1132,368,392]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1984.0">1984</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authority="Odhiambo" authorityName="Odhiambo" box="[1177,1407,367,392]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Ambonea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1177,1283,368,392]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Ambonea</emphasis>
Odhiambo
</taxonomicName>
(a junior synonym) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh" box="[391,668,404,429]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2011) Santalalean-feeding plant bugs: ten new species in the genus Hypseloecus Reuter from Australia and South Africa (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae): their hosts and placement in the Pilophorini. Australian Journal of Entomology, 50, 365 - 392. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1440 - 6055.2011.00829. x" type="journal article" year="2011">
Schuh &amp; Menard (
<number box="[599,659,404,428]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2011.0">2011</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,439,464]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Discussion.</emphasis>
This unique pilophorine genus is easily recognized by the above-mentioned characters. The significantly ovoid, thick body shape is unusual within the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[882,1011,476,501]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pilophorini">Pilophorini</taxonomicName>
, in which predominantly ant-mimetic members are accommodated (Schuh, 
<number box="[586,645,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1989.0">1989</number>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga" box="[661,914,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Yasunaga, T., Yamada, K. &amp; Artchawakom, T. (2014) Additional records and descriptions of the ant-mimetic plant bug genus Pilophorus from Thailand (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae: Pilophorini). Zootaxa, 3795 (1), 1 - 15. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3795.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Yasunaga et al., 
<number box="[855,914,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga" box="[929,1228,511,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Schuh, R. T. (2013) Morphologically novel members of the ant-mimetic plant bug genus Pilophorus Hahn found in Thailand, with descriptions of three new species (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae: Pilophorini). American Museum Novitates, 3768, 1 - 18. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 3768.2" type="journal article" year="2013">
Yasunaga &amp; Schuh, 
<number box="[1167,1228,512,536]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Such a far from antlike body shape of 
<taxonomicName box="[419,560,548,572]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[419,560,548,572]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species may have certain advantages as an adaptation to the unique host preference. Their appearance densely covered with silvery, scale-like setae (which are very easily rubbed off while being collected as in 
<figureCitation box="[409,480,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1437,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Hypseloecus species. A. H. siamensis holotype female on Scurrula sp. 1. B. H. castaneus female (SERS). C. H. castaneus male (missing scalelike setae, Nakhon Nayok). D. H. katrinae male (Nakhon Nayok). E. H. nigrobrevis holotype female (SERS)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290611/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number box="[466,480,620,644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
B 
<emphasis box="[511,542,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">vs.</emphasis>
C and 
<figureCitation box="[638,708,620,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1937,1959]" captionTargetBox="[165,1423,447,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[165,1424,447,1916]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 8. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Hypseloecus species. A. H. phuvasae holotype female (SERS). B. H. sakaerat holotype male (SERS). C. H. schuhianus male (SERS). D. H. schuhianus female (missing scalelike setae, SERS) (Nakhon Nayok)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290615/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number box="[695,708,620,644]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="8.0">8</number>
</figureCitation>
C 
<emphasis box="[740,771,621,644]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">vs.</emphasis>
D) on the body surface makes them rather cryptic and harmonious with the habitat, or surfaces of their host plants (
<figureCitation box="[843,911,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="4.[151,250,1628,1650]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1606]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[151,1437,193,1607]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 2. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Hypseloecus species. A. H. siamensis holotype female on Scurrula sp. 1. B. H. castaneus female (SERS). C. H. castaneus male (missing scalelike setae, Nakhon Nayok). D. H. katrinae male (Nakhon Nayok). E. H. nigrobrevis holotype female (SERS)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290611/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number box="[896,911,656,680]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2.0">2</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Incidentally, 
<taxonomicName box="[1102,1243,656,680]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1102,1243,656,680]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
members at first sight resemble 
<taxonomicName box="[327,469,692,716]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Coridromius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[327,469,692,716]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Coridromius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species of the subfamily 
<taxonomicName box="[771,916,692,717]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Orthotylinae">Orthotylinae</taxonomicName>
; the latter always has very tumid, developed metafemora, however (
<figureCitation box="[410,477,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 9" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1843,1865]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1820]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1437,193,1821]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 9. Habitus images of living adult individuals of Hypseloecus species and other related or similar appearing Miridae. A. H. sericosagus holotype male (Nakhon Nayok). B. H. sericosagus female (SERS). C. Coridromius testaceous of the subfamily Orthotylinae (SERS), a sample image for comparison. D. Male of a pilophorine, Aloea nairobi Schuh (at Nairobi National Museum, Kenya), associated only with Aloe monocots in the Ethiopian Region. E. Same, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290616/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number box="[462,477,728,752]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="9.0">9</number>
</figureCitation>
C).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh" box="[199,472,764,789]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2011) Santalalean-feeding plant bugs: ten new species in the genus Hypseloecus Reuter from Australia and South Africa (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae): their hosts and placement in the Pilophorini. Australian Journal of Entomology, 50, 365 - 392. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1440 - 6055.2011.00829. x" type="journal article" year="2011">
Schuh &amp; Menard (
<number box="[406,464,764,788]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2011.0">2011</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
for the first time documented that 
<taxonomicName box="[861,1002,764,788]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[861,1002,764,788]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are associated strictly with the hemiparasitic Santalalean host plants, although a single European species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Puton" authorityName="Puton" box="[1012,1194,800,824]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sthenarus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="visci">
<emphasis box="[1012,1100,800,824]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. visci</emphasis>
(Puton)
</taxonomicName>
is known to feed on 
<taxonomicName box="[151,310,836,860]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Santalaceae" genus="Viscum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="album">
<emphasis box="[151,310,836,860]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Viscum album</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. (
<taxonomicName box="[358,494,836,861]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Santalaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Santalaceae</taxonomicName>
) (
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh" box="[518,664,836,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. (1995) Plant bugs of the world (Insecta: Heteroptera: Miridae): Systematic catalog, distributions, host list, and bibliography. New York Entomological Society, New York, xii + 1329 pp." type="book" year="1995">
Schuh, 
<number box="[605,664,836,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1995.0">1995</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wachmann" box="[677,941,836,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Wachmann, E., Melber, A. &amp; Deckert, J. (2004) Wanzen. 2. Cimicomorpha: Microphysidae (Flechtenwanzen), Miridae (Weichenwanzen). Neubearbeitung der Wanzen Deutschlands, Osterreichs und der deutschsprachigen Schweiz. Die Tierwelt Deutschlands, 75, 1 - 288. [Goecke &amp; Evers, Keltern]" type="journal article" year="2004">
Wachmann et al., 
<number box="[882,941,836,860]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Wheeler" box="[954,1124,836,861]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Wheeler, A. G. Jr. (2001) Biology of the Plant Bugs (Hemiptera: Miridae), Pests, Predators, Opportunists. Cornell University Press, Ithaca and London, xv + 507 pp." type="book" year="2001">
Wheeler, 
<number box="[1064,1124,836,860]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<collectingCountry box="[1176,1278,836,861]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Thailand</collectingCountry>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[1291,1436,837,860]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="siamensis">
<emphasis box="[1291,1436,837,860]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. siamensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was discovered on inflorescence of 
<taxonomicName box="[557,655,872,896]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loranthaceae" genus="Scurrula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[557,655,872,896]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Scurrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 
<number box="[703,717,872,896]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1.0">1</number>
(
<taxonomicName box="[733,888,871,896]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loranthaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Loranthaceae</taxonomicName>
) growing on 
<taxonomicName box="[1040,1102,872,895]" class="Gastropoda" family="Ficidae" genus="Ficus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1040,1102,872,895]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Ficus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. (
<taxonomicName box="[1158,1272,872,896]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Moraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Moraceae</taxonomicName>
) in November (
<figureCitation box="[159,223,908,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1742,1764]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1721]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hosts and habitats of Hypseloecus. A. Sarika near Nangrong Waterfall, Nakhon Nayok Province, Thailand. B. Sarika near Sarika Waterfall." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290610/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number box="[212,223,908,932]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
A). Many adults and immatures of three species, 
<emphasis box="[782,1070,908,932]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName box="[782,930,909,932]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="castaneus">H. castaneus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[942,1070,908,932]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="katrinae">H. katrinae</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1126,1293,909,932]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sericosagus">
<emphasis box="[1126,1293,909,932]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. sericosagus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, were found to co-occur on flowers and fruits of 
<taxonomicName box="[553,651,944,968]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loranthaceae" genus="Scurrula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[553,651,944,968]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Scurrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 
<number box="[697,711,944,968]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2.0">2</number>
heavily parasitizing 
<taxonomicName authority="Lour." authorityName="Lour." box="[944,1216,944,967]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" genus="Homonoia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="riparia">
<emphasis box="[944,1148,944,967]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Homonoia riparia</emphasis>
Lour.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[1229,1399,943,968]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Euphorbiaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Malpighiales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Euphorbiaceae</taxonomicName>
) in March (
<figureCitation box="[240,303,980,1005]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="3.[151,250,1742,1764]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,193,1720]" captionTargetId="figure@3.[152,1435,193,1721]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURE 1. Hosts and habitats of Hypseloecus. A. Sarika near Nangrong Waterfall, Nakhon Nayok Province, Thailand. B. Sarika near Sarika Waterfall." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/290610/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Fig. 
<number box="[292,303,980,1004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
B). Flowers of 
<taxonomicName box="[477,575,980,1004]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Loranthaceae" genus="Scurrula" kingdom="Plantae" order="Santalales" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[477,575,980,1004]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Scurrula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. 
<number box="[621,635,980,1004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1.0">1</number>
and sp. 
<number box="[730,744,980,1004]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2.0">2</number>
are obviously different from each other although they are yet to be identified.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Adults of 
<taxonomicName box="[316,458,1052,1076]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[316,458,1052,1076]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are often attracted to light at night. Collection records suggest that most of the 
<collectingCountry box="[1384,1436,1052,1077]" name="Thailand" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Thai</collectingCountry>
species described below have two or more generations per year. In tropical forests, the hemiparasitic loranthaceous shrubs grow generally very high (near forest canopy), and, therefore, it is usually difficult to collect these mirids in satisfactory numbers as well as to survey their ecology.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
The majority of 
<taxonomicName box="[386,527,1196,1220]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[386,527,1196,1220]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species have hitherto been known from the Australian and Afrotropical regions (Schuh, 
<date box="[246,377,1232,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2002" valueMax="2014">
<number box="[246,377,1232,1256]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2008.0" valueMax="2014.0" valueMin="2002.0">2002–2014</number>
</date>
). Now the genus is revealed to be widely distributed in the Old World, including continental Asia. There are some more undescribed species in 
<collectingCountry box="[727,836,1268,1293]" name="Indonesia" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Indonesia</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[892,959,1268,1293]" name="Nepal" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Nepal</collectingCountry>
(Yasunaga, unpublished data), in addition to two known Asian species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Schuh, 1984" authorityName="Schuh" authorityYear="1984" box="[478,750,1303,1328]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ifugao">
<emphasis box="[478,585,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. ifugao</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh" box="[599,741,1303,1328]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. (1984) Revision of the Phylinae (Hemiptera, Miridae) of the Indo-Pacific. Bulletin of the American Museum of Natural History, 177, 1 - 476." type="journal article" year="1984">
Schuh, 
<number box="[684,741,1304,1328]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="1984.0">1984</number>
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from the 
<collectingCountry box="[859,985,1303,1328]" name="Philippines" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Philippines</collectingCountry>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Yasunaga, 2001" authorityName="Yasunaga" authorityYear="2001" box="[1039,1374,1304,1329]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="takahashii">
<emphasis box="[1039,1191,1304,1328]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">H. takahashii</emphasis>
Yasunaga, 
<number box="[1318,1374,1304,1328]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2001.0">2001</number>
</taxonomicName>
from the Ryukyus, 
<collectingCountry box="[304,372,1341,1364]" name="Japan" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Japan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="77" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
<taxonomicName box="[199,340,1376,1400]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[199,340,1376,1400]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms the second most species-rich genus in the tribe 
<taxonomicName box="[944,1073,1375,1400]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pilophorini">Pilophorini</taxonomicName>
, following a typical ant-mimetic genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Hahn" authorityName="Hahn" box="[224,417,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Pilophorus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[224,348,1412,1436]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Pilophorus</emphasis>
Hahn
</taxonomicName>
which includes more than 
<number box="[723,765,1412,1436]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="120.0">120</number>
described species. 
<taxonomicName box="[984,1110,1412,1437]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pilophorini">Pilophorini</taxonomicName>
is assumed to consist of two basic lineages, one oligophagous, non ant-mimetic group and another more or less (sometimes strikingly) antlike and predaceous group (
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga" box="[422,723,1484,1509]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Yasunaga, T. &amp; Schuh, R. T. (2013) Morphologically novel members of the ant-mimetic plant bug genus Pilophorus Hahn found in Thailand, with descriptions of three new species (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae: Pilophorini). American Museum Novitates, 3768, 1 - 18. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 3768.2" type="journal article" year="2013">
Yasunaga &amp; Schuh, 
<number box="[663,723,1484,1508]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Yasunaga" box="[738,995,1484,1509]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Yasunaga, T., Yamada, K. &amp; Artchawakom, T. (2014) Additional records and descriptions of the ant-mimetic plant bug genus Pilophorus from Thailand (Hemiptera: Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae: Pilophorini). Zootaxa, 3795 (1), 1 - 15. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3795.1.1" type="journal article" year="2014">
Yasunaga 
<emphasis box="[857,917,1484,1508]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">et al.</emphasis>
, 
<number box="[934,995,1484,1508]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2014.0">2014</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). All species of 
<taxonomicName box="[1190,1332,1484,1508]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1190,1332,1484,1508]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are now known to be associated strictly with the santalalean host plants. Of the four phytophagous (genus) groups present in Asia (
<taxonomicName authority="Reuter" authorityName="Reuter" box="[222,440,1556,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Sthenaridea" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[222,356,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Sthenaridea</emphasis>
Reuter
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Miller" authorityName="Miller" box="[457,727,1556,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Parasthenaridea" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[457,645,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Parasthenaridea</emphasis>
Miller
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Poppius" authorityName="Poppius" box="[789,1032,1556,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Lasiolabops" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[789,926,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Lasiolabops</emphasis>
Poppius
</taxonomicName>
). 
<taxonomicName box="[1054,1195,1556,1580]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1054,1195,1556,1580]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to the most speciose.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,151,1869]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">
Recent works based on both morphology and 
<collectionCode LSID="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" box="[725,786,1628,1652]" httpUri="http://biocol.org/urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15536" name="Department of Natural Resources, Environment, The Arts and Sport" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">DNA</collectionCode>
sequence data (
<bibRefCitation author="Schuh" box="[969,1241,1628,1653]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2011) Santalalean-feeding plant bugs: ten new species in the genus Hypseloecus Reuter from Australia and South Africa (Heteroptera: Miridae: Phylinae): their hosts and placement in the Pilophorini. Australian Journal of Entomology, 50, 365 - 392. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1440 - 6055.2011.00829. x" type="journal article" year="2011">
Schuh &amp; Menard, 
<number box="[1183,1241,1628,1652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Menard" box="[1255,1313,1628,1652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" refString="Schuh, R. T. &amp; Menard, K. (2013) A revised classification of the Phylinae (Insecta: Heteroptera: Miridae): Arguments for the placement of genera. American Museum Novitates, 3785, 1 - 72. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1206 / 3785.2" type="journal article" year="2013">
<number box="[1255,1313,1628,1652]" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" value="2013.0">2013</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) improved our knowledge about the phylogenetic position of the 
<taxonomicName box="[776,906,1663,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Pilophorini">Pilophorini</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<taxonomicName box="[1037,1178,1664,1688]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1037,1178,1664,1688]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is currently treated as paraphyletic in their analyses involving molecular data (unfortunately lacking any Asian species), although this genus is considered in all likelihood to be a monophyletic group, judging from the morphological characters and information on the biology. There are still quite a few undescribed species in the Oriental Region and subtropical Asia. To demonstrate the more satisfactory classification of 
<taxonomicName box="[830,971,1808,1832]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Hypseloecus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="77" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[830,971,1808,1832]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="77">Hypseloecus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, broader surveys of characters as well as of the Asian faunas are required.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
